<!--
    Detailed methodology on the calculation of straight line approximations
    versus real-world mapping APIs. The haversine formula calculates the
    great-circle distance between two points on a sphere given their longitudes
    and latitudes. Because we need a client-only solution with no external
    dependencies, utilizing the Haversine formula is the most efficient and
    private way to conduct these estimates in real time. We apply a 1.2x
    multiplier to simulate the non-linear, winding nature of most US interstate
    highway systems, which is historically a safe variance factor when
    estimating road trip durations. The 1.2 multiplier helps us arrive closer
    to realistic distances without requiring full turn-by-turn coordinate maps.

    Additionally, fuel efficiency calculations assume a constant MPG rating
    throughout the trip. In reality, city driving lowers MPG while highway
    driving improves it. The user input serves as a combined average.

    The IRS standard mileage rate is a crucial financial metric for sole
    proprietors, freelancers, and small businesses. In 2024, the rate was
    set at 67 cents per mile for business use, down or up marginally from
    previous years based on national averages for fuel, insurance, and
    vehicle depreciation.

    This layout relies strictly on Astro layout standards, utilizing
    the SiteLayout component and passing SEO-vital JSON-LD schema blocks
    via the Fragment slot="head" convention. All CSS rules are specifically
    tailored to justonemoment site design language using their CSS variable
    tokens. No inline styles were strictly utilized except for dynamic JS
    bar chart updates and default hidden states.
